HEADWORD: Mediatize
<hw>Me"di*a*tize</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp.
& p. p.</pos> <conjf>Mediatized</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Mediatizing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[Cf. F.
<ets>m⟦eacute⟧diatiser</ets>.]</ety> <def>To cause to act through an
agent or to hold a subordinate position; to annex; -- specifically
applied to the annexation during the former German empire of a smaller
German state to a larger, while allowing it a nominal sovereignty, and
its prince his rank.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The misfortune of being a <qex>mediatized</qex> prince.</q>
<rj><qau>Beaconsfield.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mediator</ent>⟦br⟧
